    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-09-23T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-09-23T14:00:00-05:00" n="742"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d742">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">702.5451/9–2344: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-23T20:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 23, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 23—7 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6321. Your 3252 September 21.<note n="60" xml:id="d742fn60">See footnote 50, <ref
                            target="#pg_1203">p. 1203</ref>.</note> Swiss Foreign Office reports
                    chief Foreign Interests Section of Swiss Consulate Nice (removed to Grenoble)
                    arrived Nice September 8 and agreed with American Officer in charge civil
                    affairs that Swiss Consulate now at Nice would continue protection Americans in
                        district<note n="61" xml:id="d742fn61">A memorandum of September 26 by a
                        divisional assistant of the Division of Special War Problems (Correll)
                        stated that the Department’s records indicated that at that time
                        approximately 75 American nationals were receiving monthly financial
                        assistance from the Swiss Consulate at Nice (temporarily at Grenoble); in
                        addition to this number it was anticipated that a considerable number of
                        Americans formerly resident at Nice who had left because of German pressure
                        or who had been forcibly evacuated to other parts of France would return to
                        Nice as soon as feasible (702.5451/9–2344).</note> until functions taken
                    over by representative State Department. Postal service having been
                    reestablished September 12 Swiss Consulate forwarded relief receipts to
                    qualified recipients for September payments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
